                     <interp inst="t18311201-213-person1669" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am pew-opener at <placeName id="t18311201-213-crimeloc1141">Tavistock chapel, Drury-lane</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18311201-213-crimeloc1141" type="placeName" value="Tavistock chapel, Drury-lane"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18311201-213-crimeloc1141" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-213-off1139 t18311201-213-crimeloc1141"></join>. On the 27th of October I saw a strange man go into Mr. Pearman's pew - it was not the prisoner; but he is something like a man who gave me a note that night for a gentlemen, who, he said, would come to take a sitting.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-213-person1670">
                  JOHN 
                  PEARMAN
               <interp inst="t18311201-213-person1670" type="surname" value="PEARMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-213-person1670" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-213-person1670" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My family attend Tavistock chapel. I left these books there on the 23rd of October; they are mine.</p>

               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, stating that he was a book-hawker, and had taken the books in exchange for others.</p>
